Quebec and Canada face a crucial test on November 30th, 1998 as Quebecers go to the polls in the first provincewide elections since the separatists narrowly lost a referendum on independence in 1995.
The modern separatist movement began about 30 years ago and is based on deeply rooted feelings that Quebec has not been treated fairly by English speaking Canada.
Lucien Bouchard is expected to become Parti Quebecois leader and Quebec premier at the end of January 1996, reviving a crusade for Quebec independence from Canada.
Bouchard decided to take over the job from Parti Quebecois and Quebec Premier Jacquese Parizeau after October 30 referendum on Quebec independence was defeated.
Since the separatist movement began in Quebec in the 1960s, the sentiment for breaking up Canada appeared to gain momentum.
The Inuit and the Cree natives of northern Quebec, and some English-speaking residents in western Quebec and Montreal has said they want to remain in Canada if Quebec votes to break away from the country.
However, they don't think the Calgary accord will make much difference in terms of keeping the French-speaking Province of Quebec in Canada.
The Supreme Court of Canada began a landmark hearing on whether the French-speaking province of Quebec has the right to secede unilaterally, and ruled that Quebec can't separate from the country unilaterally.
